As someone who should really follow her own advice, I feel like at least giving it out should help a bit for people who want to grow a following and aren't just using these platforms as a fan or to interact with friends. Hope this helps in some way.

If you are growing, but the community feels impersonal or distant and yoy want more meaningful interaction with followers, try picking up one of the community platforms as a way to interact with more dedicated fans.

If your main output of content is on a community platform, it's likely you won't see the growth you want, as their algorithm isn't really made to show you things you don't already know from people you already know. Try switching your main output to a Growth platform.

Community platforms are things like Twitter, twitch, snapchat, tumblr, discord. They are much harder to grow on, but people will follow you there in order to have a more personal connection with a creator they enjoy.

Growth platforms are things like youtube, Instagram, tiktok, and deviants. Platforms that you create content on and for in order to grow your audience. They are often less personal for content creators who want to "get bigger".
I just verbalized a theory I've had in my head for a while now. There are 2 types of social media platforms if you are a content creator. Growth platforms, and Community platforms. 🧵

@MeloBeeNatural Continuing from that thought, I consider Twitter to be a secondary media source. One where I can be more myself to followers of other socials to interact more personally. You have grown platforms (insta, youtube) and you have community platforms (twitch, Twitter)
